{"status":"OK","data":{"id":3073087,"identifier":"DVN/NVPJK0","persistentUrl":"https://doi.org/10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0","protocol":"doi","authority":"10.7910","publisher":"Harvard Dataverse","publicationDate":"2018-01-10","storageIdentifier":"s3://10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0","latestVersion":{"id":132344,"storageIdentifier":"s3://10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0","versionNumber":2,"versionMinorNumber":0,"versionState":"RELEASED","productionDate":"Production Date","lastUpdateTime":"2018-05-02T07:54:58Z","releaseTime":"2018-05-02T07:54:58Z","createTime":"2018-01-14T18:28:16Z","license":"CC0","termsOfUse":"CC0 Waiver","metadataBlocks":{"citation":{"displayName":"Citation Metadata","fields":[{"typeName":"title","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Replication Data for \"When Do You Get Economists as Policy-Makers?\""},{"typeName":"author","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"authorName":{"typeName":"authorName","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Hallerberg, Mark"},"authorAffiliation":{"typeName":"authorAffiliation","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Hertie School of Governance"}},{"authorName":{"typeName":"authorName","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Wehner, Joachim"},"authorAffiliation":{"typeName":"authorAffiliation","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"LSE"},"authorIdentifierScheme":{"typeName":"authorIdentifierScheme","multiple":false,"typeClass":"controlledVocabulary","value":"ORCID"},"authorIdentifier":{"typeName":"authorIdentifier","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"orcid.org/0000-0002-1951-308X"}}]},{"typeName":"datasetContact","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"datasetContactName":{"typeName":"datasetContactName","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Wehner, Joachim"},"datasetContactAffiliation":{"typeName":"datasetContactAffiliation","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"LSE"},"datasetContactEmail":{"typeName":"datasetContactEmail","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"j.h.wehner@lse.ac.uk"}}]},{"typeName":"dsDescription","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"dsDescriptionValue":{"typeName":"dsDescriptionValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Stata data and do files to reproduce analysis (Stata 14.2).\r\n\r\nAbstract: We analyze when economists become top-level “economic policy-makers,” focusing on financial crises and the partisanship of a country’s leader. We present a new dataset of the educational and occupational background of 1200 political leaders, finance ministers, and central bank governors from 40 developed democracies from 1973 to 2010. We find that left leaders appoint economic policy-makers who are more highly trained in economics and finance ministers who are less likely to have private finance backgrounds but more likely to be former central bankers. Finance ministers appointed during financial crises are less likely to have a financial services background. A leader’s exposure to economics training is also related to appointments. This suggests one crucial mechanism for affecting economic policy is through the selection of certain types of economic policy-makers."},"dsDescriptionDate":{"typeName":"dsDescriptionDate","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"2017-11-03"}}]},{"typeName":"subject","multiple":true,"typeClass":"controlledVocabulary","value":["Social Sciences"]},{"typeName":"keyword","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Financial crisis"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Finance ministry"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Central bank"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Finance"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Fiscal policy"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Monetary policy"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Partisanship"}}]},{"typeName":"language","multiple":true,"typeClass":"controlledVocabulary","value":["English"]},{"typeName":"depositor","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Wehner, Joachim"},{"typeName":"dateOfDeposit","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"2017-11-03"}]}},"files":[{"description":"Stata data","label":"HW_BJPS_dataverse_dataset_4 january 2018.dta","restricted":false,"version":1,"datasetVersionId":132344,"dataFile":{"id":3106377,"persistentId":"doi:10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0/DA5SYY","pidURL":"https://doi.org/10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0/DA5SYY","filename":"HW_BJPS_dataverse_dataset_4 january 2018.dta","contentType":"application/x-stata","filesize":301595,"description":"Stata data","storageIdentifier":"s3://dvn-cloud:160f5eebaf0-6f7296c14848","rootDataFileId":-1,"md5":"c75b4de5f522a6e3ea68cd152281ae0c","checksum":{"type":"MD5","value":"c75b4de5f522a6e3ea68cd152281ae0c"}}},{"description":"Stata do file","label":"HW_BJPS_dataverse_do file_4 january 2018.do","restricted":false,"version":1,"datasetVersionId":132344,"dataFile":{"id":3106378,"persistentId":"doi:10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0/KX9CRX","pidURL":"https://doi.org/10.7910/DVN/NVPJK0/KX9CRX","filename":"HW_BJPS_dataverse_do file_4 january 2018.do","contentType":"application/x-stata-syntax","filesize":30859,"description":"Stata do file","storageIdentifier":"s3://dvn-cloud:160f5eebe6d-a11c28f348c6","rootDataFileId":-1,"md5":"601081cad8db2102a3bb05a24910672f","checksum":{"type":"MD5","value":"601081cad8db2102a3bb05a24910672f"}}}]}}}